# Coding Discipline

## Before Writing Code

- If the requirement is unclear, brainstorm with user first — do NOT guess
- Understand the business logic thoroughly before implementing — no patchy code
- Follow the project's HMVC structure; read the `dev` skill if needed

## When Corrected

- If the user corrects a mistake or points out a wrong approach, immediately invoke the `lessons` subagent to record it before continuing
- If a code review flags a Critical issue, invoke the `lessons` subagent to record it

## While Writing Code

- Vertical slice, not horizontal — implement one feature end-to-end through all layers before starting the next
- YAGNI: do not write code for things not yet needed
- Single Responsibility: each class/method does exactly one thing
- No hardcoded values, no magic numbers — use config or named constants with clear context
- Do not declare constants carelessly — only when reused or when naming a value adds clarity
- Only mock external dependencies (APIs, email, file system) — never mock to bypass internal logic

## Examples

```ruby
# BAD: magic number
def expired?
  created_at < 30.days.ago
end

# GOOD: named, configurable
EXPIRATION_PERIOD = 30.days
def expired?
  created_at < EXPIRATION_PERIOD.ago
end

# BAD: mocking internal logic to make test pass
allow(operation).to receive(:call).and_return(true)

# GOOD: test through public interface with real input
result = described_class.call(params: valid_params)
expect(result).to be_success
```
